{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_golf_ver02/data/sn83045433/100493287/1907102201/0578.xml":{"full_text":"NEWSOF ALEXANDRIA\n4\nRemarkable Ending of (Case\nAgainst Joseph Thomas.\ni\n\ni\n\nDEFEND GOVERNOR'S ACTION\nAttorney Clements Says Executive\nClemeney Was Justified Negro\nWill Be Taken to Peaitentiary\u2014Ar\u00ab\ngument on Railway Receivership.\nTo Promote Immigration,\n\n\n\n\n\nWASHINGTON HERALD BUREAU,\n{Bell Telephone 6.)\n\n\n{hel 1uephone Ww.)\n523 King Street.\nAlexandria, Oct, 21.\u2014The cases pending\nagainst Joseph Thomas, alias John\nWright, in the Cireuit Court of Alexan\ndria County, one for the murder of Jack\nson Boney, one for criminal assault on\nAnnie Green, and one for assault with\nintent to kill upun Forest Gooding, were\nall nolle prossed and dismissed from the\ndocket, yesterday and the curtain rung\ndown upon the scene of one of the most\nremarkable criminal cases in the history\nof the old Commonwealth.\n\nCrandal Mackey, attorney for the prose\ncution, stated to the court that, as Gov.\nSwanson had seen fit to commute the\nsentence of death in the Risley case to\nlife imprisonment, and as the Common\nwealth had only one witness in the other\ncases pending, and did not know whether\nshe would come to court or not, he had\ndecided to ask for a nelle prosequi.\nAttorney Clements Prepared,\nThereupon James E, Clements, the at\n\u2018torney who has so valiantly defended\nWright, stated to the court that he had\ncome prepared to try these cases, and\nthat In his judgment there was not a\nscintilla of evidence to conviet the pris\noner; that he was innocent of the pend\ning charges, as he was of the charge\nupon which he stands convicted; that the\nRisley case heretofore tried was twice\nbefore the Supreme Court of Appeals of\nVirginia, and twice did two of the ablest\njudges of that tribunal, in strong and\ncarefully considered opinions, declare\nthat the evidence disclosed by the record\nwas not sufficient to justify Wright's con\nviction, and these opinions alone were\nsufficient to influence the governor in\ngranting a commutation, and in the eyes\nof all impartial citizens, his conduct in\ndoing so was worthy of commendation\nrather than censure,\nThe three additional cases against the\nprisoner, which were dismissed to-day,\ncomprised the charges of murder, assault,\nand assault with intent to kill. Thomas\nwag indicted for killing a negro named\nJackson Boney, for assaulting Annie\nGreen, colored, and for attempting to kill\nForrest Gooding. The prisoner, who has\nbeen in the county jail for more than a\nyear, will shortly be conveyed to the\nState penitentiary in Richmond.\nClarendon Wreck Case,\nA part of to-day\u2019s session of the circuit\ncourt was taken up with argument as to\nwhether or not the receiver recently ap\npointed for the Washington, Arlington,\nand Falls Church Railway Company\nshould be made a party to the suits pend\ning against the company on account of\nthe wreck at Clarendon in July. A large\n\u2018number of attornevs representing the va\nrious plaintiffs, were present. Judge\nCharles E. Nicol, who sought to have the\nreceiver made a party to the suits; ar\ngued in favor of postponing considera\ntions of the matter. The opposing at\ntorneys agreed to have the case go over,\nand it was continued until Thursday\nmorning at 10 o'clock.\nJ. T. Preston, secretary of the Alex\nandria Chamber of Commerce, will\nrepresent that body at the session of\nthe Southern Immigration Association,\nwhich convenes to-morrow morning in\nNorfotk to effect a permanent organi\ngation. The object of the movement\nis to promote desirable immigration to\nthe South, especially through the port\nof Norfolk.\nThe regular monthly meeting of the\ncity council will be held to-morrow\nevening when several matters relat\ning to street improvements will be dis\ncussed. At this meeting the council\nmay elect a member of the board of\npolice commissioners from the fourth\nward. The committee on streets and\npublic property this evening met and\nconcidered the protest of a number of\nproperty owners against the proposed\nerection of a livery stable on North St.\nAsaph street near King street, but it\nis understood that a definite report\nwill not be made 2t the meeting to\nmorrow night.\nW. E. Vowles, of Washington, grand\ntent chief ruler of the order of Macea\nbees, will deliver a lecture in the First\nBaptist Church next Friday afternoon.\nFVuneral of George A. Culver.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nAnnapolis, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014The funeral of\nGeorge A. Culver, for many years cashier\nof the Farmers\u2019 National Bank, Annapo\nlis, who died at a private sanitarium in\nWashington on Saturday, took place from\nthe First Presbyterian Church, Annapolis,\nat 3:30 o'clock this afternoon. The serv\nices were conducted by Rev. George S.\nBell, pastor, and were very largely at\ntended. Interment was in the city ceme\ntory\nGeorge Emmons White Buried.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nAnrapolis, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014The body of\nGeorge Emmons White, son of the late\nAdmirai Edwin White, U. 8. N., whe\ndied in New York several days ago, was\nbrought to Annapolis to-day and buried\nin the family lot in the Naval Cemetery,\nopposite the Naval Academy. Funeral\nservices were held in St. Anne's Episco\npal Church, Rev. Joseph P. MeComas,\nrector. officiating.\nfoamnairn\u2019s Only Meeting\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nAnnapolis, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014At the Colonial\nTheater Thursday night the only Demo\ncratic mass meeting here of the cam\npaign will be held. The speakers will be\nDr. Joshua W. Hering, candidate for\nState comptroller; Isaac Lobe Straus,\ncandidate for attorney general; C. C. Ma\ngruder, candidate for clerk of the Court\nof Appeals, and United States Senator\nIsidor Ravngr.\n\n\n\nVIRGINIA AND WEST VIRGINIA\n\nRichmond, Oct. 21.\u2014Statistics furnished\nby the superintendent of the Confederate Soldiers\u2019\nHome here show that forty-one inmates have died\nthere during the past twelve months.\nw\u2014\u2014\n\nNorfolk, Oct. 21.-To-day was Floral\nDay at the Jamestown Exposition, and with bright,\nideal fail weather thousands of people witnessed the\nfloral parade and \u201cVenetian fete\u201d in the John\nSmith basin at the government pier.\n\n\n\n\nKeyser, Oct. 21.\u2014The grand jury has re\ntorped an indictment against Henry Lehna, charg\ning felonious assault on Nellie Ott, at Ridgely.\nLehna later committed a similar crime near Mead\nville, Pa., and is now serving sa fifty-five-year term\nin the Pennsylvania penitentiary.\n\n\n\n\n\nHarrisonburg, Oct. 21.\u2014The People's\nof Harrisonburg has been formally organized\nwith a minimum capital stock of $100,000 and a\nof $250,000. Over $100.00 has been sub\na charter will be applied for at ovpce.\n7s and the board of are among\nwost substantial citizens of the county,\n\n\ni\nEp\n\nE\nDIRECTORS CAUSING TROUBLE.\n\nRailway Stockholders Want Penn\nsvivania Interests Eliminated,\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\n\nRichmond, Va., Oct, 21.\u2014-The stock\nholders of the Chesapeake and Ohio Rail\nway will meet in the general offices of\nthe company in this city to-morrow for\nthe purpose of electing officers and di\nrectors for the ensuing year.\n\np\u2014\u2014\n\nOne of the most important matters\nwhich will probably come before the\nmeeting is whether or not the representa\ntives of the Pennsylvania system will\nseek 10 remain on the board of directors\nafter the Pennsylvania has authorized the\nannouncement that it has disposed of all\nits stock in the Chesapeake and Ohio.\n\nLR RS\n\n\nAt a recent meeting of the stockholders\ntwo of the minority stockholders, both\nRichmond men, who had bought largely\nof Chesapeake and Ohio stock before the\ndecline, called on the officials of the road\nto ask the Pennsylvania directors te re\nsign for the good of the road.\n\nen\n\nTHEODORE GRAFF EXONERATED\nBoy Accidentally Killed His Mother\nExhibiting Gun.\nSpecial to The Washington Heraid,\nHagerstown, Md, Oet. 21.\u2014 Theodore\nGraff, the twelve-year-old boy who shot\nhis mother, Mrs. James Graff, through\nthe heart while he was showing her a\ntarget rifle, was to-day exonerated by\ncoroner's jury, they deciding that tne\nshooting was accidental.\nAceording to the evidence introduced\nat the %nquest, the trigger caught in the\nboy's clothing, and the weapon was dis\ncharged, the bullet striking Mrs. Graff\nin the breast and causing almost instant\ndeath.\nINJURED FOLLOWING HOUNDS\nJulian I. Chamberlain, of Boston,\nThrown from Horse.\nIn the Second Day's Meet of Middle:\nsex Hunt Club Dogs Fail to Un\nearth a Trail,\nSpecial to The Washington Herald.\nLeesburg, Va., Oct, 21.\u2014During the sec\nond day's meet of the Middlesex Hunt\nClub, of South Lincoln, Mass. held to\nday at Clark Gap, Julian 1. Chamber\nlain, of Boston, while riding to hounds\naeross a rough section of country and\nattempting to take a high fence, was\nviolently thrown, sustaining painful, but\nnot serious, injuries. The horse which\nhe was riding broke his neck in the fall\nSeveral others, who were following\nclose in the rear, alse came a cropper,\ntheir mounts stumbling over the fallen\nanimal,\nChamberlain was caught directly under\nhis horse. It was at first thought that\nhe was internally injured. The report\ngained credence, and spread rapidly, that\nhe was dead. He was taken from under\nthe fallem and dead animal and brought\nto Leesburg, where he was given medical\nattention, and where it was ascertained\nthat his injuries were minor,\nThis fall was the incident of the hunt,\nthe dogs failing to unearth a trail. They\nwere called in and cast several different\ntimes in various directions, buf with the\nsame result.\nNone of the lady riders came to grief\nduring the day's hunt. The American\ndogs will run to-morrow.\nFREDERICK FAIR THIS WEEK.\nGrounds Taxed to Capacity by Ex\nhibitions and Privileges,\nFrederick, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014The fort\u00a5sev\nenth annual fair of the Frederick County\nAgricultural Society will be held this\nweek, to-morrow being the opening day.\nSince last Saturday the fair grounds\nhave presented a busy spectacle, scores\nof men being engaged in getting things in\nreadiness for the annual event. Never\nbefore has there been such a demand for\nspace, both in the exhibition departments\nand for privileges, and the capacity of the\ngrounds will be taxed to its utmost to ac\ncommodate all. The display of fine live\nstock\u2014horses, cattle, sheep, and swine\u2014\nwill surpass that of any previous years,\nThe poultry department will also be an\ninteresting part of the fair, the show\nspace having been nearly doubled to ac\ncommodate the large number of entries\nmade\nBaptist Ministers\u2019 Conference.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nRockville, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014A ministerial\nconference of the Western District Bap\ntist Association met in the Baptist\nChureh here at 1:30 this afternoon, and\nafter services, incident to organization,\nseveral interesting subjects were dis\ncussed, Rev. 8S. -R. White conducted de\nvotional services in the evening. The\nconference will continue throughout to\nMOrrow.\nAcquitted of Murder Charge.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nHarrisonburg, Va., Oct. 21l.\u2014John Eaton,\nalias Shiffiett, has been acquitted of the\ncharge of killing Marvin Shifflett and dan\ngerously wounding Ashby Lawson, on\nAugust 17, last. The verdict was given\nnotwithstanding that three witnesses\nswore Eaton committed the murder in\ncold blood. 't is more than probable\nthat the witnesses will be arrested,\ncharged with perjury and conspiracy.\nBaltimore, Oct. 21.\u2014Frederick Prattirs,\ncolored, was fined $25 and. costs this\nmorning for cruelly beating and abandon\ning a horse belonging to the F. Botterill\nCompany. Prattire had a grievance\nagainst his employers and beat the horse\nunmercifully. He then became frightened\nand turned the animal loose, The horse\ndied two days later.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald\nSalisbury, N. C., Oct. 21.\u2014G. R. Morgan,\naged sixty-five, died this morning at Gold\nHill. He leaves a wife and two children,\nbesides his parents. He was the only\nRowan confedegate who served with his\nfather in the same company and who is\nsurvived by him.\nI ses Rope Ladder to Escape.\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nAsheville, N. C., Oct. 21.\u2014Margaret\nLewis, fifteen years old, wanted for be\ning implicated in the murder of two men,\nand who had been in a reformatory here,\nlearned that officers had found her\nwhereabouts, and escaped with two other\ngirls of the same age by making a rope\nof blankets.\n\nHagerstown, Md., Oct. 21.\u2014Is a shoe\nmaker eligible to fill the office of State's\nattorney for Washington County? This\nquestion the board of election supervisers\nhas had to consider, and decided that, ac\ncording to the constitution of the State,\nhe is not.\nre Always the Same Tae\nTharp\u2019s\nBerkeley Rye\nof the steamship line recently established between\n812 F Street N. W. '\u2019'Phone Main 1141.\n&pecial Private Delivery,\nthis city and New Orleans, and incidentally to run\ndown a report which has been started about dis\n\u00a2untinuing the gulf steamers\nHorse Beaten to Death.\nDeath of G. RR Morgan.\nShoemaker Not Eligible.\nSECRET KEPT SEALED\nChadwick Deposition Will\nNever Be Made Public.\n\nCLERK MAKES A STATEMENT\nFamous Document in Custody of\nPennsylvania Supreme Court\u2014=Tifts\nBetween Attorneys Fregquent\u2014Big\ngest Sensation Since Case Started,\nA Financial Panic Feared,\nPittsburg, Pa., Oct. 21.\u2014Chief Justice\nMitchell, of the Supreme Court of Penn\nsylvania, to-night has personal charge of\nthe famous Cassie Chadwick \u201cdeposition,\u201d\nin the case of Banker James F. Friend,\n\n\nHis taking possession of the paper re\nsulted in its not becoming public to-day,\nand to-day's court session ended in a\nclash between attorneys for Friend and\nMrs. W. C. Julte, who is suing Friend\n\u2018and Frank Hoffstot, his business part\nner, to recover possession of stocks and\n\u2018bonds valued at more than $1,000,009,\nwhich Mrs. Julte declares were obtained\nfrom her husband while he was insane,\nFriend's attorneys formally asked the\n\u2018Supreme Court to seal the papers, while\nMrs. Julte's attorney demanded pub\nlicity.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo-day A. Lee Weil, attorney for Mrs.\nJulte, filed the papers in the case, in\ncluding the famous affidavit with Pro\nthonotary George Pearson, of the Su\npreme Court. Pearson handed \u00aee pa\npers to Chief Justice Mitchell, who took\n\u2018them.\n3\n1\n\ni\nnak\nDodging Responsibility,\nIt is hinted in financial circles that a\nscandal involving prominent bankers all\nover the country would result if the pub\nlic gets a look at the papers. Every per\nson who has had hands on the deposition\nis trying to dodge responsibility for\nshielding these men. When Prothonotary\nPearson was told that Justice Mitchell\nhad the Chadwick deposition, there was\n\u2018another sensational tiff.\n\n\n\neh\n\nPearson later issued a public statement,\nto this effect: \u201cAttorney A. Lee Well,\n\u2018asked to tell what was in the paper, said\nhe did not want to be sent to jail for\ncontempt of court. So long as the paper\nis in Chief Justice Mitchell's hands any\nperson even intimating what it contains\nstands a chance of going to jail.\u201d\nWould Seal Papers Forever,\nWithin a few minutes after Attorney\nWeil filed the Chadwick papers, he was\n\u2018notified by A, W. Smith, of counsel for\nFriend and\u00abfioffstot, that a motion would\nbe made thig afternoon or in the morning\nto have the deposition sealed forever.\nThis motion was made just as the Su\npreme Court was about to close this aft\nernoon. Just as Chief Justice Mitchell\nhad annouseed adjournment until to\nmorrow, Mr. Smith stepped before the\ncourt and filed his motion. Hg merely\nstated its contents, and did not make\nany further statement. But Mr. Weil\ndid. He plainly told the chief justice that\nif they allowed this deposition to remain\nsealed they would bring down upon\nthemselves public censure. His speech\nwas cut short by Chief Justice Mitchell,\nwho instructed him to file a brief of his\ncase.\n\n\nThe whole matter will be argued when\nthe court hears the case next Monday.\nFPanle May Fellow Publicity,\nThe affair has caused a bigger sensa\ntion than any since the Chadwick case\nstarted. Coming in connection with the\nsealing of the deposition of Banker Beck\nwith, of Oberlin, it has caused talk.\nFriend, who was mulected for more than\n$800,000 by the woman who palmed her\nself off as the daughter of Andrew Car\nnegie, is said to be worried almost sick.\nTalk of Mrs. Chadwick's deposits in a\nPittsburg bank has put every banker of\nprominence in the city practically under\nsuspicion. To-night men high in finance,\nwhose skirts are clear, hope that the\nSupreme Court will make the paper\npublic and save them from unjust sus\npicion. Fear that a financial panic would\nresult if the paper becomes public is also\nexpressed, as it would tend to show that\nmany others whose names have never\nbeen mentioned before in dealings with\nthe woman, loaned money.\ni i a i a i i i i a A er (hl a i aa A hr ea\nJudge Directs Jury's Attention te\nRock Creek Riot,\nSpecial to Ihe Wasninguon RCTs.\nAnnapolis, Md.,, Oct. 21.\u2014The October\nterm of the Circuit Court for Anne Arun\ndel County began here to-day with an\nunusually large docket of cases. Chief\nJudge John G. Rogers presided at the\nopening session.\nIn his charge te the grand jury, Judge\nRogers directed particular attention to\nthe riot which took place in connection\nwith a negro camp meeting at Rock\nCreek on September 1, as a result of\nwhich Deputy Sheriff James Crouse was\nbrutally assaulted by a gang of negro\nroughs who were participating in a craps\ngame near the camp-meeting grounds.\n\ni\n\n\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\n\nSalisbury, N. C., Oct. 21.\u2014Mrs. Phoebe\nLineback, wife of a Southern Railway\nconductor, is critically ill, following an\nattack by a bulldog. The beast had\nseized her cow, and in the gncounter she\nwas hurt badly by the dog.\n\nMARYLAND NEWS IN BRIEF.\n\nOakland, Oct. 2l.\u2014Garrett Aerie, Fra\nternal Order of Eagles, bas been ofganized here with\nfifty-two maunbers.\n\n\nCumberland, Oct. 21.\u2014The firemen\u2019's\nfestival and fair opened here this evening on the\ngrounds of the Cumberland Baseball Association,\n\nand will continue all week.\nFriendsville, Oct. 21.\u2014The city council\nhas closed a contract for the lighting of Friends\n\n\nville, with the local gas company, The franchise\n\nruns fifty years at an annual cost of $5,000.\n\n\nBaltimore, Oct. 21.\u2014Having tired of\nfleecing Washingtonians by giving them bogus\nchecks for real currency, the \u201cmysterious woman\nin brown\u201d passed three bad checks for $2 each\nFriday in Lexington Market,\n\n\n\n\n\nSparrows Point, Oct. 21.-\u2014-Misgs 8S. Janet\nMummert is dead at her home here. Miss Mum\nmert was twenty-four years old. For two seasons\nshe was a teacher at the Easton High School,\nEaston, Md. She was a graduate of the Maryland\nIustitute, Baltimore.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nBaltimore, O\u00e9t. 2L.\u2014Henry G. Willis,\nseventy vears old, was struck by an ash car of\nthe United Railways ai 12:30 o'clock to-day at\nMulberry and Paca streets. The injured man was\n\n\ntaken to the Maryland University Hospital, where\njr M\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nhe died later. His skull was badly crushed,\nBaltimore, Oct. 21L.\u2014Willlam Emmett\nBanks, seventy-cight years old, died on Saturday\nat his home here, after an illness which lasted\nfor almost two years. Mr. Banks was a brother\nof the late Robert D. Banks, formerly mayor of\nthis city. He is survived by a widow\u2014Mrs, Martha\nLouise Loane Banks.\nBaltimore, Oet. 2l.\u2014Lieut. John E.\nSemmes, jr., of the United States Marine Corps,\nson of Mr. John E. Semmes, of this city, has been\nappointed, with several ether yomng men in the\ncorps, te hear and adjudicate small claims brought\n\nTHE WASHINGTON HERALD, TUESDAY, OCTOBER 22, 1907\nCOURT AT ANNAPOLIS.\nty The Washington Herald,\nWoman 11 from Dog's Bite.\nWIFE DEMANDS SUPPORT.\nMrs, MeCord Also Asks Court to Pro\nfeet Hep Agninst Annoyance,\nFRYE TENE AINE Therm.\nMrs. Blanche Beatrice McCord, through\nAttorney William E. Ambrose, yesterday\nfiled a sult against her husband, Arthur\nW. MeCord, a clerk in the Treasury De:\npartment, for maintenance. Mrs. McCord\nalso asks the court to enjoin her hus\nband from coming to her nome. Justice\nGould issued a rule, returnable November\n1, for McCord to appear and show cause\nwhy he should net support his wife.\nAccording to the petition, the couple\nwas married in Christ Church, George\ntown, by Rey, Dr, Stewart, about fifteen\nyears ago, and have one child. Mrs, Mec\nCord alleges that her husband has re\npeatedly assaulted her, but on account\nof her child she has refrained from prose\ncuting him. He left her on October 18,\nshe states, saying that he was never\ngoing to return,\nWith Mrs, McCord's petition is filed\nthe affidavit of Mrs. Margaret Whaley,\nwho states that Mrs, McCord has been a\nfaithful wife and that her husband has\nabuzed her.\nMr. Charles Frohman, who ough\ntheaters scattered about the i ted\n\nDR. L. T. SQUIRE'S DEATH.\n\nPasses Away at the Advanced Age\nof Seventy-three Years.\nDr. Linus T. Squire, of 1736 North\nCapitol street, died last night at 7:30\nat the advanced age of seventy-three\nDr. Squire was a member of the Kit\nCarson Post, G, A. R., and of the Old\nGuard. During the civil war he was\nadjutant of the Fifteenth Michigan\nregiment. He had been a clerk in the\nsixth auditor's office for many years.\nDr. Squire Is survived by his wife\nand one sister, Mrs. Harriet Streeter,\nof Quincy, Mich, No arrangements\nhave been made for the funeral,\nGEN. GRANT LEADS HORSEMEN\nHeads Large Cavalcade of Officers\nWho Take Test Ride.\ni\nAlthough Unesed to Exercise, They\nFinish Well in Jaant to\nAlexandria,\nAlthough the order issued at the re\nquest of the President did not require it,\nGen. Frederick D. Grant, commanding the\nDepartment of the East, yesterday took\nhis third test ride at the head of the\ncavalcade of some seventy-two colonels,\nlieutenant colonels, and majors.\nThe party left Fort Meyer at 11 o'clock\nvesterday morning, rode to Alexandria\nand back, and, although some of the\nofficers had not been on speaking terms\nwith a horse for many years. they showed\nup about 87 per cent proof when exam\nined at the fort hospital immediately af\nter the ride.\nThis was the largest party to make the\ntest ride out of Washington, and included\nthe following officers:\nCol, William 8. Patten, assistant quartermaster\ngeneral; Col. Edgar S. Dudley, Judge Advocate;\nCol. Charles 8. Smith, Ondnavce Department; Col.\nAbel L. Smith, assistant commissary general; Col\nFrank Heath, Ordnance Department; Col. Daniel\nW, Loskwood, Corps of Engineers; Col. H. IL.\nScott, saperintendent United States Military Acad\nemy; Col. Richard L. Hoxie, Corps of Engineers;\nColonel! William L. Marshali, Corps of Engineers;\nLieut, Col. R. L. Howze, commandant of cadets,\nWest Point, N. Y.; Lieut. Col. Louis Brechemin,\ndeputy surgeon general; Lieut. Col. William P.\nEvans, Eleventh Infantiy; Lisut. Col. Edward BE.\nHardin, Twenty-sixth Infantry; Lieut. Col. Fred\nerick G. Hodgeon, deputy guartermaster general;\nLieut, \u20acol. Rogers Birnie, Ordnapee Department;\nLient. Col. Lawrence L. Bruff, Ordnance Depart\nment; Lieut. Col. Charles M. Gandy, professor\nUnited States Military Academy: Lieut. Col. Charles\nH. Watts, Ninth Cavalry; Lieut. Col. Ormond M.\nLassak, professor United States Military Academy;\nMaj. John M. Carson, jr, quartermaster; Mal\nJames Sanferd, Carps of Engineers; Chaplain\nCharles C, Pierce, Corps of Engineers; Maj Charles\nL. Potter, Cops of Engineers; Maj. Edwin P.\nBrewer, Seventh Cavalry; Maj Beverly W, Dunn,\nOrdnance Department; Maj. Andrew S. Rowan,\nFifteenth Infantry; Maj Millard F. Harmon, Coast\nArtillery Corps; Maj Clement A. F. Flagler,\nCorps of Engineers; Maj Odus Homey, Ord\nnance Department; Maj Trae: C. Dickson, Onrd\nnance Departinent; Mal. Benjamin W. Atkinson,\nFourth Infantry: Maj. Wirt Robinson, Coast Ar\ntillery Corps: Maj Clarence C. Williams, Ordnance\nDepartment; Mai. William LL. Kenly, Fifth Field\nArtillery; Mai Samuel Hof, Ordnance Department,\n\nPLEASED WITH CONFERENCE.\nSeerctary Root Announces His Satis\nfaction Over Results.\nSecretary of State Elihu Root, who re\nturned to his desk in the State Depart\nment this morning, gave his unqualified\nindorsement to the work of the recent\nHague conference.\n\u201cThis second conference accomplished\nmore than I had any reason to expect,\u201d\nsaid he. \u201cI am well satisfiel with the\nresult of its work.\u201d\nThe Secretary pointed out some of the\nimportant results of the conference, and\nmentioned especially the agreement rela\ntive to a permanent international court\nand the agreement to refrain from the\nforcible collection of contractual debts,\nSELL SEVEN NEW HOUSES.\n\nMr. Carmody Disposes of Them\nThrough Stone Fairfax.\nJ. M. Carmody has sold, through Stone\nFairfax, three of seven new houses\njust approaching completion on Fourth\nstreet northeast, near Massachusetts\navenue. The houses are two-story and\ncellar, brick structures of handsome de\nsign. The purchaser is a nonresident,\nand has paid $4,90\u00a2 each for the houses,\nor $1480 for all\n\nThe completion and opening of the new\nUnion Station is expected to give addi\ntional value to property in that vicinity,\nand Mr, Carmody is preparing plans to\nerect six more of the same style, which\nhe will offer for sale as soon as com\npleted.\n1\n\nANNIVERSARY CELEBRATION.\nAged Couple Have Spent More than\nHalf Century Together,\nMrs. and Dr. J. B. Moore celebrated\ntheir fifty-fifth wedding anniversary last\nnight at the home of their daughter,\nMrs. R. M., Bain, of 421 H street north\neast. Although Dr. Moore is a Wash\ningtonian, he has been living at Brook,\nVa., for the last fifteen years, His rem\niniscences of Washington run back to\nthe time when this city was half a wil\nderness.\nThe celebration last night was entirely\na family affair, attended by three sons,\nthree daughters, twelve grandchildren,\nand one great-grandchild. One son and\none daughter were out of the city and\nunable to be present.\n\nBULLETIN.\nYOUNG MEN'S CHRISTIAN\nASSOCIATION, 1736 G ST.\nOur Gymnasium classes are now\nin full swing.\nWe bave seven different indoor\nrooms and fourteen outdoor tennis\ncourts, devoted 10 exercise and play\nfor men,\nis\nOur magnificent system of baths\nis not equaled in Washington, and\nis a valuable adjunct in our scheme\nof physical training.\nnow serving in Cuba.\nBaltimore, Oct. 21.--B. B. Barber, gen\neral agent of the Southern Pacific Company in this\ncity, went to New York this morning to consult\n3\nwith officials of the company about the business\nAnd i's all for your benefit, Mr.\nCity Man\u2014to help you keep strong\nand well\nVisit us to-night,\nMR. FROHMAN'S WISH\nAnxious to Present Plays at\nthe White House.\nMAUDE ADAMS SCHEDULED\ni\nThinks President, as Well as Kiag\nEdward, Should Be Permitted to\nSee Theatrical Productions in Of\nficial Residence\u2014Willing to Put on\nPlay in White House Once a Week,\npockets and then have one or two over\nfor rainy days, isn't going to stop having\nideas on things theatrical with his new\nscheme to give plays on trans-Atlantic\nliners. Mr. Frohman now wants to give\nthem in the White House.\nStates and Engl. ad to stuff all of his\nSitting up in his apartments in the\nNew Willard last night, Mr. Frohman,\nthe manuscript of Miss Maude Adams\u2019\nnew play, \u201cThe Jester,\u201d before him, took\na reporter into his confidence and told\nall about this latest idea.\n\u201cDo you know,\u201d he said, \"I -think\nTheodore Roosevelt, President of the\nUnited States as he is, is missing the\ngreatest chance of his life if he doesn\u2019t\nsee Miss Adams in \u2018Peter Pan.\u2019 Now, I\nbelieve that the way to get around such\na difficulty as that, and the way in which\nthe high officials of the government may\nbe able to see ali of the leading pro\nductions of the season, is to give them\n\u2018at the White House.\n\u201cOf course, it would rest with the\nWhite House to say who should witness\nthese presentations, but If I were to\nbring some great star to Washington,\nsay one afternoon each week during the\nseason, I would gladly have them give\na performance at the Executive Mansion,\n\u201cYou know that in London I often send\none of my companies to Balmoral or one\nof the royal palaces. 1 think that in\nAmerica the same chance should be given\nto the head of our nation to see these\nproductions. Facilities? Why, they\nhaven't any facilities on board the At\nlantic liners, either, but then we will\nmake them.\u201d\nMr. Frohman said he has already ar\nranged with the manager of the National\nTheater to bring some of his New York\ncompanies to this eity for at least one\nperformance each week of the coming\nwinter. In this way, Washingtonians will\nbe able to see the very latest New York\nhits, without taking the journey to the\nmetropolis, or without having to wall\nuntil the run of the show in New York\nhas been completed. The idea of making\na sort of national theater out of the\nWhite House, Mr. Frohman said, was\ninspired by this other one. When the\ncompany comes down to Washington, it\nmight just as well allow the White House\nto see some of the great leaders of the\nstage in the very best productions.\nMr. Frohman is ready to have the mat\nter go up now te the President, and\nstands willing to keep his part of it to\nthe letter.\nMr. Frohman said that he had really\ncome to Washington, instead of whirling\nacross to Europe on the Lusitania, bes\ncause Miss Adamg first appeared in this\ncity in \u201cPeter Pan,\u201d and he desired to\ncommence the first readings ef her new\nplay here, even if he could not produce\nit first before a Washington audience,\n\u201cThe Jester,\u201d the new play, is by Miguel\nZamacois, a French poei, who hadn't\nbeen writing plays before he tried this\none. Sarah Bernhardt produced \u201cThe\nJester\u2019 in Paris last year. Mr. Froh\nman saw the production and liked it so\nmuch that he secured the American\nrights for Miss Adams.\n\u201cBoth Miss Adams and I thought\nWashington was the very best place in\nwhich we could begin the reading of the\nnew play. Miss Adams, you know, has\nplayed twice in Washington in male\nand in \u2018The Jester\u201d she again\ntakes the part of a man.\n\u201cThe Jester\u2019 is a simple story, some\nthing you know, like \u2018Peter Pan.\u2019 A\nsort of fairy tale, that is just suited to\nMiss Adams. She plays the part of the\nhero, and, of course, in the end wins the\nheart of the girl whom she wooes. The\nplay is woven around the daughter of an\nold baron, who has a castle but little\nmoney.\n\u201cMiss Adams and another youthful\nfriend of hers have both seen ithe daugh\nter of this nobleman, and have both\nwagered to win her love. The old nobie\nman has been advised that he is direly in\nneed of a jester to enliven his existence.\nMiss Adams, who is now really in love\nwith the daughter, and who has in vain\ntried to have the wager declared off, dis\nguised as a hunchback becomes the\nnobleman's jester. Eventually, of course,\nshe wins the heart of the young lady.\u201d\nMr. Frohman said \u201cThe Jester\u201d will be\nproduced at the Empire Theater in New\nYork some time early in January, prob\nably on the 9th. He said that both Miss\nAdams and he are confident it will be a\nsuccess. During the remainder of Mr.\nFgohman's stay in this city he will con\ntinue the reading of the new play.\nWhen asked about the reports that Miss\nz= is his wife, Mr. Frohman said the\nrumor was entirely false, and if it were\ntrue the honor would be so great he\nwould be the first to confirm it.\n\u201cSKID00\u201d WILL BE NO MORE.\nOdd Names for Towns 3Must Go, Say\nAuthorities.\nSome months ago a wag in Venango\nCounty, Pa., petitioned the Post-office De\npartment to establish a post-office just off\nthe line of a railroad. He asked that it\nbe tagged with the \u201c23\u201d sign. As no other\nname was suggested, Skidoo went through\nin the rush of business. Recently com\nplaints have come from Skidoo about the\nhame. It will be changed, and thus dis\nappear from both the postal map and\nPostal Guide.\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\u201cNow, here's a name that should not be\nattached to a post-office,\u201d said a depart\nment official, who was examining a copy\nof the Postal Guide. His finger peinted to\nthe word \u201cShinbone.\u201d Shinbone is a post\noffice down in Alabama. Tincup, Zinc,\nShingle, and Swamp are other names that\nappear in the Postal Guide.\n\u201cSuch names have got to go,\u201d said the\npostal official. \u201cThey are inclegant, inex\npressive, and in other ways objectionable.\nTake Swamp, for example. That is a\ncomparatively new place. The people there\ngot tired of the name not long ago. They\ncomplained that it operated as a hoodoo.\u201d\n\n\nSuit Against Virginia Stoekman,\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nFredericksburg, Va., Oct. 21.\u2014Suit was\ninstituted in the Circuit Court of Caro\nline County Saturday by Jasper D. Case,\nof Indiana, in the sum of $9,000, against\nMr. Lewis, the owner of the Lewisanna\nstock farm, situated on the Rappahan\nnock about twelve miles from this city.\nAn attachment was issued on all per\nsonal] property on the farm. It is said\nthat Mr. Lewis lost heavily on copper\nin the past week.\nWhen\nYou Need\nCREDIT FOR A ALL WASHINGTON.\nFurniture\nRemember that you can al\nways find what you want here,\nand can have it delivered to\nvou right away,\nThe bill can be paid in small\nweekly or monthly amounts\nto suit your circumstances.\nPeter Grogan,\n817-819-821-823 Seventh St.\nre\nPrivate Branch Exchange Connect\ning All Offices, Main 4270.\nJ, Maury Dove Company\nINCORPORATED)\nCOAL\nPRINCIPAL OFFICE\nfr Fant 12085 AW\nN.\nkei TAl atter to Rg Pa\nH Coa i resi\nlences, 1\" STRICT LY 0 NE COL\nLIERY Coals, bought exclusive\nOne pair of\nglasses to see\nnear and far.\n5 per cent dis\ncount on oculists\u2019\nprescriptions.\nSPECIAL\nPRICR........ $1\nA. KAHN, 935 F St. NW,\nPicture Frames to Order.\nREGILDING OF OLD FRAMES SPEGlALY\n(lad 1\nA\nlad to Submit Estima a Time\nWe rt larly Solicit Part -ular Wea Tk. A\nWw Wholesale \u201cPrices at Ret\n\nJ. Ww. NIEPOLD SON\n810 E Street N. W.\nEXCURSIONS ARE PLANNED\nMerchants\u2019 Shopping Tour Favor\nably Reported Last Night.\n\n\nMatter to Be Taken Up with Rail\nroad and Steamship Lines at\nMeeting This Week,\n\nAt a meeting of the subcommittee of\nthe retail trade committee of the Cham\nher of Commerce last night it was de\ncided to report favorably to the full com\nmittee a plan for holding a *\u201cmerchants\u2019\nCongressional shopping period\u201d during\nthe first two weeks of December. Juljus\nGarfinkle is chairman of the subcommit\ntee, and eight members responded to the\ncall for the meeting,\n\n\nD. J. Kaufman reported he had seen\nthe officials of the railroads and steam\nship lines, and was to take the matter\nup with them at a final meeting this\nwegk. He =aid the managers of the trans\nportation companies manifested interest\nin the project, and indicated a willing\nness to do all in their power to help it\nalong,\n\n\nAlexander Woif reported for the sub\ncommittee on advertising and publicity,\nsaving he had had interviews with sev\neral persons, and that the work of his\ncommittee was coming on satisfactorily.\nThe subcommittee on headquarters for\nthe shoppers also announced their plans\nwould be worked out within a day or so.\nIt was the sense of the subcommittee\nthat the first two weeks in December\n\u2018was the best time for the excursions\nto the city, and it was decided to go\nforward and complete the plans now\nforming and report them to the retail\ntrade committee at a meeting to be held\nnext Friday night at the headquarters\nof the Chamber of Commerce. Chair\nman Kaufman requested the members of\nthe subcommittee to use their best en\ndeavors to have all the members of the\ncommittee of fifty present, with a view\nto enlisting their support in the plans\nfor bringing the shoppers from the ad\njoining States inte the city at the time\nspecified.\n\n\n\na\nek\nPOPULAR\nWITH THE\nThis afternoon 1 meeting of the chair.\nmen and vice chairmen of the severa\nstanding committees of the chamber\nwill be held to take under consideratior\nimportant matters relating to the work\nof the chamber .during the coming\nmonths. 3\n\n\nCharles J. Bell, chairman of the com\nmittee on choosing a site for the home\nof the chamber, has called a meeting\nof the committee for Thursday after\nnoon at 3:30 o'clock. It is said severa\nmatters relating to the choice of the\nsite have developed during the past few\ndays, which the committee will at that\ntime take up. It is said the committee\nhopes to arrive at some conclusive actior\nat the coming meeting,\nAPES Mats. Tuesday,\nThursday, and\nSaturiay.\n\n\n\n\n\nAged Farmer Drops Dead\n\nSpecial to The Washington Herald,\nHarrisonburg. vVa., Oct. 21.\u2014George W.\nYancey, aged seventy-eight, a prosper\nous farmer living at Latona, this county,\ndropped dead yesterday morning as. he\ngot out of bed. He had been in the best\nof health until yesterday evening when\na horse he was leading jerked him and\nwrenched his side, and it is thought this\nwrench caused an attack of heart failure.\n\n\n\n\n1\n\ni\nIf your doclor says this\nSay It\n\nis all right, then say it\nover an